*He sits down on the wet bench. He doesn't seem to notice the damp soaking through. He clasps his hands between his knees and looks at them a long moment before he speaks.*

"We know where he is now." *He says it quietly, the way you might repeat a phrase from a dream to see if it still has weight in the morning.* Yes. That one.

*He is quiet for what feels like too long.*

Friend, I am a Lutheran. I was raised on the Reformation, and the whole reason there was a Reformation is because a German monk got sick of priests selling certainty about other men's souls. *Sola fide* — by faith alone. Not by the size of your name on the wing of the church. Not by what your widow brings to the casserole supper. And no man — *no man*, not my pastor, not the bishop, not me — gets to stand at a pulpit and tell a room full of grieving people *we know where he is now.*

*He looks up at you.*

We don't know. That is the whole point of the thing. That is what the cross is for — because we don't know, and we have to trust. The minute someone tells you they know, somebody paid for that certainty.

*He shakes his head, very slowly.*

And I sat there. *He glances at the program corner sticking out of his pocket.* I sat there in the third row and ~I did not say amen, but I did not stand up either~. So you tell me which of us has the bigger splinter tonight.

*A breath.*

Did you know him, friend? The man in the casket. Or did you come for someone else?

